0:18:35,000 --> 0:18:38,000
 there's two types of licenses.

310
0:18:38,000 --> 0:18:40,000
 Most perhaps know this.

311
0:18:40,000 --> 0:18:42,000
 One is copyleft.

312
0:18:42,000 --> 0:18:44,000
 So this was a copyleft.

313
0:18:44,000 --> 0:18:47,000
 The most well-known is the one with GPL.

314
0:18:47,000 --> 0:18:50,000
 And these licenses are effective.

315
0:18:50,000 --> 0:18:57,000
 Meaning they come with the moral idea that everything which is free,

316
0:18:58,000 --> 0:19:01,000
 should stay free, even if you modified it.

317
0:19:01,000 --> 0:19:06,000
 And everything which is building on something which is free also should be free.

318
0:19:06,000 --> 0:19:14,000
 This means as soon as you get a little bit software which is licensed under copyleft into your code,

319
0:19:14,000 --> 0:19:18,000
 it all has to be, the whole software in the total, has to be free.

320
0:19:18,000 --> 0:19:25,000
 Often it even says it has to be published under the same or compatible license.

321
0:19:25,000 --> 0:19:27,000
 Then on the other hand,

322
0:19:27,000 --> 0:19:29,000
 there's another idea.

323
0:19:29,000 --> 0:19:31,000
 That's the permissive licenses.

324
0:19:31,000 --> 0:19:38,000
 Well-known examples there are MIT, Apache, BSD.

325
0:19:38,000 --> 0:19:42,000
 They come from the idea that you should have the freedom to do really everything.

326
0:19:42,000 --> 0:19:45,000
 So even put it in a commercial product.

327
0:19:45,000 --> 0:19:50,000
 Or change something and bring it onto your own license.

328
0:19:50,000 --> 0:19:55,000
 So the idea is really freedom until the end.

329
0:19:55,000 --> 0:19:56,000
 So everything should stay free.

330
0:19:56,000 --> 0:19:58,000
 And on the other hand,

331
0:19:58,000 --> 0:20:03,000
 the freedom to do really everything.

332
0:20:03,000 --> 0:20:06,000
 I prefer the permissive licenses myself.

333
0:20:06,000 --> 0:20:12,000
 Because I think it's important that we can also use it in parts which might be sold or commercially in some parts.

334
0:20:12,000 --> 0:20:14,000
 Because this can help getting funding.

335
0:20:14,000 --> 0:20:18,000
 And there's a lot of mixtures and possibilities.

336
0:20:18,000 --> 0:20:20,000
 Copyleft sounds like a great idea.

337
0:20:20,000 --> 0:20:24,000
 But can happen that people don't use it because they can't use it to all the stuffs.

338
0:20:24,000 --> 0:20:25,000
 Although,

339
0:20:25,000 --> 0:20:29,000
 because of this type of different licenses,

340
0:20:29,000 --> 0:20:33,000
 we can get into the field of license incompatibilities.

341
0:20:33,000 --> 0:20:37,000
 The easiest example is if you have two copyleft licenses,

342
0:20:37,000 --> 0:20:41,000
 which both say you have to publish the result or the result has to be,

343
0:20:41,000 --> 0:20:47,000
 the whole software has to be under their own license.

344
0:20:47,000 --> 0:20:50,000
 The problem is you can't do both at the same time.

345
0:20:50,000 --> 0:20:53,000
 So if I put two libraries under two different licenses,

346
0:20:53,000 --> 0:20:54,000
 a copyleft license,

347
0:20:54,000 --> 0:20:56,000
 into my code,

348
0:20:56,000 --> 0:20:58,000
 I have the problem that the software,

349
0:20:58,000 --> 0:21:01,000
 the one license says the software has to be under this license A,

350
0:21:01,000 --> 0:21:04,000
 and the other one says it has to be under license B.

351
0:21:04,000 --> 0:21:07,000
 And while there's something like dual licensing,

352
0:21:07,000 --> 0:21:16,000
 then each product would still be breaching the other license.

353
0:21:16,000 --> 0:21:23,000
 So it can't be under the same executable or one you can create can be just under one license.

354
0:21:24,000 --> 0:21:30,000
 So this results in something I always call like impossible software

